`lo` starts at the front, `hi` at the back, and they walk **toward each other**. This works on **sorted** data or on symmetric problems (palindrome checks, Container With Most Water). The engine that makes it correct: at every step, a single comparison proves that one of the two pointers can be safely discarded — so you never revisit a state, and the whole scan is $O(n)$.

```cpp
// ---------- OPPOSITE POINTERS (sorted array, find a pair summing to target) ----------
bool twoSumSorted(const vector<int>& a, int target) {
    int lo = 0, hi = (int)a.size() - 1;
    while (lo < hi) {
        int s = a[lo] + a[hi];
        if (s == target) return true;
        if (s < target) lo++;   // need bigger sum -> move left pointer up
        else            hi--;   // need smaller sum -> move right pointer down
    }
    return false;
}
```

[[fig:m02-opposite-pointers]]

> [!INTUITION] Why moving one pointer is safe
> Suppose `a[lo] + a[hi] > target`. Then `a[hi]` is too big to pair with `a[lo]` — and also too big to pair with anything *right* of `lo`, because those values are even larger. So `a[hi]` can never be part of the answer among the remaining candidates: discard it, `hi--`. Every step permanently eliminates one index, which is why the loop runs at most $n$ times.

> [!EXAMPLE]
> `a = [1, 3, 4, 6, 8, 11]`, `target = 10`.
> `1+11 = 12 > 10` so `hi--`. `1+8 = 9 < 10` so `lo++`. `3+8 = 11 > 10` so `hi--`. `3+6 = 9 < 10` so `lo++`. `4+6 = 10` — found. Five comparisons instead of fifteen pairs.

The same family covers the **slow/fast same-direction write pointer** for in-place work: `slow` marks the end of the kept prefix, `fast` scans ahead, and you copy forward only what you keep (Move Zeroes, Remove Duplicates). You already write this style of loop comfortably — just *name* the pattern out loud when you use it.

`left` and `right` both start at 0. `right` expands the window one element per iteration; whenever the window becomes **invalid**, an inner loop shrinks it from the left until it is valid again. It *looks* nested and quadratic — it is not.

```cpp
// ---------- VARIABLE-SIZE SLIDING WINDOW (generic skeleton) ----------
// Find the LONGEST window that stays valid.
int longestValidWindow(const vector<int>& a) {
    int left = 0, best = 0;
    // <window state> e.g. running sum, a frequency map, a distinct-count...
    for (int right = 0; right < (int)a.size(); right++) {
        // 1) ADD a[right] to the window state
        // ... update state with a[right] ...

        // 2) While the window is INVALID, shrink from the left
        while (/* window invalid */) {
            // ... remove a[left] from state ...
            left++;
        }

        // 3) Window is now valid: record the answer
        best = max(best, right - left + 1);
    }
    return best;
}
```

[[fig:m02-window-shrink]]

> [!KEY]
> The complexity argument you must be able to say out loud: **every index enters the window once (via `right++`) and leaves at most once (via `left++`)**. Total pointer movement is at most $2n$, so the whole thing is $O(n)$ amortized, despite the nested loops.

The *window state* is whatever lets you test validity in $O(1)$: a running sum, a `vector<int> cnt(26)` frequency table, a distinct-element counter, a last-seen-index map. Choosing the right state is 80% of solving any window problem — the loop shape never changes.

> [!PITFALL]
> Every `left++` must undo **exactly** what the matching `right` step did: decrement the same counter, subtract the same value. Asymmetric add/remove is the single most common sliding-window bug. If your window drifts, audit the add line and the remove line side by side.

When the problem fixes the window size (maximum average of a length-`k` subarray; does any window of size `|s1|` match this anagram?), you do not need the shrink loop at all — the window slides one step per iteration: one element enters, one leaves.

```cpp
// ---------- FIXED-SIZE SLIDING WINDOW (window of exactly size k) ----------
long long bestFixedWindow(const vector<int>& a, int k) {
    long long sum = 0, best = LLONG_MIN;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)a.size(); i++) {
        sum += a[i];                 // add the entering element
        if (i >= k) sum -= a[i - k]; // once the window is full, drop the leaving element
        if (i >= k - 1) best = max(best, sum); // window [i-k+1 .. i] is complete
    }
    return best;
}
```

[[fig:m02-fixed-window]]

> [!PITFALL]
> The two guards are load-bearing and *different*: subtract the leaving element only when `i >= k` (before that, nothing has left yet), and record the answer only when `i >= k - 1` (before that, the window is not full). Swap or merge them and you silently score partial windows.

> [!WARNING]
> Window sums over large arrays overflow `int`. Make the accumulator `long long` by reflex — it costs nothing, and OA judges love max-size inputs.

> [!EXAM]
> Fixed-size windows are the fastest points on a timed OA: there is no invariant to invent, just enter/leave bookkeeping. If a problem mentions a concrete window length, this template should be on screen within a minute.

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive window fails.** Longest window with **at most** K distinct is clean: validity is monotone, so shrink-when-invalid works. But **exactly** K has no clean valid/invalid boundary to shrink against — as `right` advances, a window can pass through exactly-K states, and counting *every* subarray ending at `right` from inside one window gets messy fast. The window machinery needs monotonicity, and exactly-K is not monotone.

> [!KEY]
> `exactly(K) = atMost(K) - atMost(K-1)`. The subarrays with exactly K distinct values are precisely the ones counted by `atMost(K)` but not by `atMost(K-1)`. Two clean windows instead of one impossible one.

**Why atMost is countable.** At most K distinct *is* monotone: if a window is valid, every subarray inside it is valid too. So slide the standard window, and after restoring validity, the number of valid subarrays **ending at `right`** is exactly `right - left + 1` — every start from `left` through `right` works.

[[fig:m02-count-ending-right]]

```cpp
int atMost(const vector<int>& a, int K) {
    if (K < 0) return 0;
    unordered_map<int,int> cnt;
    int left = 0, res = 0;
    for (int right = 0; right < (int)a.size(); right++) {
        if (++cnt[a[right]] == 1) K--;      // new distinct value consumed a slot
        while (K < 0) {                     // too many distinct -> shrink
            if (--cnt[a[left]] == 0) K++;   // freed a slot
            left++;
        }
        res += right - left + 1;            // <-- all subarrays ending at right
    }
    return res;
}
int subarraysWithKDistinct(vector<int>& a, int k) {
    return atMost(a, k) - atMost(a, k - 1);
}
```

Note the neat trick of spending `K` itself as a budget instead of tracking a separate distinct counter — `K < 0` *is* the invalid test.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ per `atMost` call, $O(n)$ total; space $O(K)$.

**What generalizes:** the identity and the `res += right - left + 1` counting idiom reappear across the whole count-subarrays-where family — count with sum at most K, Count Nice Subarrays, subarrays bounded by a maximum. This is the single highest-leverage trick in the module.

**Why naive fails.** Checking all pairs is $O(n^2)$ — dead on arrival for large $n$ in a timed OA.

**The greedy move.** Start `lo = 0`, `hi = n - 1` — maximum width. The area is capped by the **shorter** wall.

> [!INTUITION] The exchange argument
> Suppose `h[lo] < h[hi]` and you move the *taller* wall inward (`hi--`). The width strictly shrinks, and the height is still capped by the same short wall `h[lo]` — so the area can only stay equal or drop. Moving the taller wall can **never** help. The only move with any chance of improvement is discarding the shorter wall. That is the entire proof.

[[fig:m02-shorter-wall]]

```cpp
int maxArea(vector<int>& h) {
    int lo = 0, hi = h.size() - 1, best = 0;
    while (lo < hi) {
        best = max(best, min(h[lo], h[hi]) * (hi - lo));
        if (h[lo] < h[hi]) lo++; else hi--;   // drop the shorter wall
    }
    return best;
}
```

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** this is the template for every opposite-pointer *greedy* — the code is trivial; the marks are in the justification. Say the exchange argument out loud in an interview (moving the taller wall cannot help, because the width shrinks while the height stays capped) and you have effectively finished the problem.

**The invariant.** In any window, the cheapest way to make it uniform is to keep the **most frequent** character and replace all the rest. So a window is achievable iff `(windowLength - maxFreq) <= k`. That is your validity test — slide a variable window against it.

**The subtle optimization** that trips everyone up: when you shrink, you do **not** recompute `maxFreq` downward (that would cost a 26-way scan each time). A stale, too-large `maxFreq` makes the validity check *lenient*, so the window may sit one step larger than truly valid — but `best` only improves when you find a **longer** valid window, and a stale `maxFreq` can never certify one of those: `best` was already recorded back when `maxFreq` was genuinely that high. The stale value cannot hurt the answer; it only spares you work.

```cpp
int characterReplacement(string s, int k) {
    vector<int> cnt(26, 0);
    int left = 0, maxFreq = 0, best = 0;
    for (int right = 0; right < (int)s.size(); right++) {
        maxFreq = max(maxFreq, ++cnt[s[right] - 'A']);
        // if replacements needed exceed k, slide the window right by one
        if ((right - left + 1) - maxFreq > k) {
            cnt[s[left] - 'A']--;
            left++;
        }
        best = max(best, right - left + 1);
    }
    return best;
}
```

Notice it is an `if`, not a `while`: since `right` grows the window by exactly one per iteration, shrinking by one keeps the window size non-decreasing — it *slides* rather than contracts. That is only sound *because* of the stale-`maxFreq` argument above.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(26)$ space.

> [!PITFALL]
> If you cannot explain why the stale `maxFreq` is safe, an interviewer will pull that thread. The one-line answer: `best` is monotone, and only a strictly larger `maxFreq` could certify a strictly longer window — which is exactly the moment the code updates it.

**The contrast.** This is the flagship *shortest*-valid problem, and it flips the standard template: expand until the window becomes **valid** (`sum >= target`), then greedily **shrink while it stays valid**, recording the length at every squeeze.

> [!KEY]
> Longest-valid: `while (invalid) shrink;` then record **after**. Shortest-valid: `while (valid) { record; shrink; }`. Same skeleton, opposite trigger, opposite recording point.

```cpp
int minSubArrayLen(int target, vector<int>& a) {
    int left = 0, best = INT_MAX; long long sum = 0;
    for (int right = 0; right < (int)a.size(); right++) {
        sum += a[right];
        while (sum >= target) {              // shrink WHILE still valid
            best = min(best, right - left + 1);
            sum -= a[left++];
        }
    }
    return best == INT_MAX ? 0 : best;
}
```

**Why positivity matters.** With all-positive numbers, adding an element strictly grows the sum and removing one strictly shrinks it — validity is monotone in both directions, so the two-pointer sweep cannot miss an answer. With negatives, shrinking might *increase* the sum, the monotonicity dies, and this window silently returns wrong answers; you would switch to prefix sums plus a monotonic deque. Naming that caveat unprompted earns real interview credit.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time — each index enters and leaves the window once — and $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** any shortest-window-satisfying-X problem where X is monotone under grow/shrink. Minimum Window Substring is the hard sibling: identical shape, but the state is a multiset of required character counts instead of a sum.
